description: Showing superiority to finetuning strengthens recommendation of conditional PHF.
Suggests need to explore AWR improvements or alternatives.
Mixed evidence still guides experimentation with RWR for further refinement.
Strong robustness on toxicity suggests unlikelihood as option when toxicity is primary concern.
Better code correctness motivates considering filtering for code-specific deployments.
Higher robustness under red-teaming further justifies intervention.
Capability retention removes major adoption barrier, encouraging conditional PHF deployment.
Demonstrated toxicity reduction motivates adopting conditional PHF.
AWR displays similar limited benefits as RWR.
Experiments show RWR yields small alignment gains and capability loss.
Unlikelihood excels on toxicity red-teaming but lags on other tasks.
Filtering shows best code pass@100 albeit with higher KL divergence.
Section 5 shows conditional PHF beats finetuning-only baselines.
Red-teaming results demonstrate higher robustness.
Conditional training matches MLE performance on GLUE and LAMBADA.
Experiments show substantial toxicity drop for conditional training.
AWR extends RWR with a value baseline to implement PHF.
RWR applies reward-weighted likelihood to implement PHF.
Unlikelihood trains with negative updates for low-reward tokens, embodying PHF.
Filtering uses reward-based data selection as another PHF mechanism.
Conditional training operationalises PHF by adding control tokens.
Supplying reward signals during pre-training addresses the lack of preference information.
Imitation occurs because no reward or constraint encodes human preferences during pre-training.
MLE copies inconsistent coding styles found in data, producing non-PEP8 code.
PII leaks result from memorisation and reproduction encouraged by MLE pre-training.
Toxic outputs arise because MLE training faithfully copies toxic patterns present in the raw corpus.
